'''Extinctive prescription''' is a legal term referring to the expiration of a legitimate inheritance as the result of prolonged failure to claim said inheritance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.internationallawoffice.com/Account/Login.aspx?ReturnUrl=https://www.internationallawoffice.com/Newsletters/Litigation/South-Africa/Rudolph-Bernstein-Associates/Extinctive-prescription-in-a-construction-context|title=My account - International Law Office|website=Internationallawoffice.com|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://roselawblog.wordpress.com/2013/01/15/what-is-extinctive-prescription-and-why-is-it-so-important/|title=What is “extinctive prescription” and why is it so important?|date=15 January 2013|website=Roselawblog.wordpress.com|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref> Extinctive Prescription is enshrined in United Kingdom by the [[Prescription Act 1832]].<ref> "Prescription Act 1832". By Practical Law Company. Retrieved April 20, 2013.</ref>

